        <odd id="ref28">
            <head>Early American History Note</head>
            <p>Nathan Sellers was a prominent engineer who specialized in the papermaking industry in Philadelphia. This collection of his papers consists of a variety of documents related to his life and career. It includes two volumes of commonplace books, a notebook he kept while serving in the Philadelphia Common Council, records of his early work as a surveyor, and an assortment of financial and business records.</p>
            <p>The commonplace books contain primarily legal verbiage Sellers copied and was likely related to the demands of his business. One book does contain a few pencil sketches of an individualâ€™s profile.</p>
            <p>His memorandum books (#37) record his daily activities for the years 1773, 1774, and 1776. One is also an almanac. Sellers used the calendar to note various financial transactions and daily activities.</p>
            <p>In addition to the bound volumes, the collection has a large number of miscellaneous papers. These are organized by theme and include manuscript essays on a range of subjects such as religion, poetry, and the like. Although it arranged by topic, some of the material is in the form of personal correspondence that discusses the specified topic but also discusses more quotidian concerns. Although this material is listed as part of the Nathan Sellers collection, it includes material from many other members of the family, such as Rembrandt Peale, and other sorts of materials, such as calling cards, fragments of hair, business accounts, and legal documents.</p>
        </odd>
